6" alt=3D"Octal Number System"> </div> </div> <div class=3D"desc col-sm-6 c=
ol-md-6"><h1>Octal Number System</h1><p>The Octal Number System is another =
type of computer and digital numbering system which uses the Base-8 system<=
/p> </div> <div class=3D"social_box_buttons-excerpt"> </div> </div> <div cl=
ass=3D"section row"> <div class=3D"single-wrap col-md-12"> <div class=3D"co=
ntent-cont"><p>The <strong>Octal Numbering System</strong> is very similar =
in principle to the previous hexadecimal numbering system except that in an=
 octal number system, a binary number is divided up into groups of only 3 b=
its, with each group or set of bits having a distinct value of between 000 =
(0) and 111 (&nbsp;4+2+1 =3D 7&nbsp;).</p><div class=3D"openimg"><img fetch=
priority=3D"high" decoding=3D"async" src=3D"https://www.electronics-tutoria=
ls.ws/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/octal-numbers.jpg" alt=3D"octal numbering =
system" title=3D"Octal Numbering System" width=3D"300" height=3D"225"></div=
><p>Octal numbers therefore have a range of just =E2=80=9C8=E2=80=9D digits=
, (0, 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7) making them a Base-8 numbering system and theref=
ore, <span class=3D"mtxt">q</span> is equal to =E2=80=9C8=E2=80=9D.</p><p>T=
hen the main characteristics of an <strong>Octal Numbering System</strong> =
is that there are only 8 distinct counting digits from <span class=3D"ntxt"=
>0</span> to <span class=3D"ntxt">7</span> with each digit having a weight =
or value of just 8 starting from the least significant bit (LSB).</p><p>In =
the earlier days of computing, octal numbers and the octal numbering system=
 was very popular for counting inputs and outputs because as it works in co=
unts of eight, inputs and outputs were in counts of eight, a byte at a time=
.</p><div class=3D"code-block code-block-10" style=3D"margin: 8px 0; clear:=
 both;"><div class=3D"htlad-content-top-left tude-ads" data-unit=3D"Electro=
nicsTutorials/article"><div id=3D"content-top-left" class=3D"htl-ad"></div>=
</div></div><p>As the base of an <strong>Octal Numbers</strong> system is <=
span class=3D"ntxt">8</span> (base-8), which also represents the number of =
individual numbers used in the system, the subscript <span class=3D"ntxt">8=
</span> is used to identify a number expressed in octal. For example, an oc=
tal number is expressed as:&nbsp;&nbsp;<span class=3D"ntxt">237<sub>8</sub>=
</span></p><p>Just like the <a class=3D"inlink" href=3D"https://www.electro=
nics-tutorials.ws/binary/bin_3.html">hexadecimal numbering system</a>, the =
=E2=80=9Coctal number system=E2=80=9D provides a convenient way of converti=
ng large binary numbers into more compact and smaller groups. However, thes=
e days the octal numbering system is used less frequently than the more pop=
ular hexadecimal numbering system and has almost disappeared as a digital b=
ase number system.</p><h3>Representation of an Octal Number</h3><table clas=
s=3D"table1"><tbody><tr><td>MSB</td><td colspan=3D"7">Octal Number</td><td>=
LSB</td></tr><tr><td style=3D"width:50px;">8<sup>8</sup></td><td style=3D"w=
idth:50px;">8<sup>7</sup></td><td style=3D"width:50px;">8<sup>6</sup></td><=
td style=3D"width:50px;">8<sup>5</sup></td><td style=3D"width:50px;">8<sup>=
4</sup></td><td style=3D"width:50px;">8<sup>3</sup></td><td style=3D"width:=
50px;">8<sup>2</sup></td><td style=3D"width:50px;">8<sup>1</sup></td><td st=
yle=3D"width:50px;">8<sup>0</sup></td></tr><tr><td>16M</td><td>2M</td><td>2=
62k</td><td>32k</td><td>4k</td><td>512</td><td>64</td><td>8</td><td>1</td><=
/tr></tbody></table><p>As the octal number system uses only eight digits (0=
 through 7) there are no numbers or letters used above 8, but the conversio=
n from decimal to octal and binary to octal follows the same pattern as we =
have seen previously for hexadecimal.</p><p>To count above 7 in octal we ne=
ed to add another column and start over again in a similar way to hexadecim=
al.</p><div class=3D"code-block code-block-8" style=3D"margin: 8px 0; clear=
: both;"><div class=3D"htlad-content-middle tude-ads" data-unit=3D"Electron=
icsTutorials/article"><div id=3D"content-middle" class=3D"htl-ad"></div></d=
iv></div><p class=3D"text-center"><span class=3D"mtxt">0, 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6,=
 7, 10, 11, 12, 13, 14, 15, 16, 17, 20, 21=E2=80=A6.etc</span></p><p>Again =
do not get confused, <span class=3D"ntxt">10</span> or <span class=3D"ntxt"=
>20</span> is <b>NOT</b> ten or twenty it is <span class=3D"ntxt">1 + 0</sp=
an> and <span class=3D"ntxt">2 + 0</span> in octal exactly the same as for =
hexadecimal. The relationship between binary and octal numbers is given bel=
ow.</p><h3>Octal Numbers</h3><table class=3D"table1"><tbody><tr><td style=
=3D"width:160px;">Decimal Number</td><td style=3D"width:160px;">3-bit Binar=
y Number</td><td style=3D"width:160px;">Octal Number</td></tr><tr><td>0</td=
><td>000</td><td>0</td></tr><tr><td>1</td><td>001</td><td>1</td></tr><tr><t=
d>2</td><td>010</td><td>2</td></tr><tr><td>3</td><td>011</td><td>3</td></tr=
><tr><td>4</td><td>100</td><td>4</td></tr><tr><td>5</td><td>101</td><td>5</=
td></tr><tr><td>6</td><td>110</td><td>6</td></tr><tr><td>7</td><td>111</td>=
<td>7</td></tr><tr><td>8</td><td>001 000</td><td>10 (1+0)</td></tr><tr><td>=
9</td><td>001 001</td><td>11 (1+1)</td></tr><tr><td colspan=3D"3">Continuin=
g upwards in groups of three</td></tr></tbody></table><p>Then we can see th=
at 1 octal number or digit is equivalent to 3 bits, and with two octal numb=
er, <span class=3D"ntxt">77<sub>8</sub></span> we can count up to 63 in dec=
imal, with three octal numbers, <span class=3D"ntxt">777<sub>8</sub></span>=
 up to 511 in decimal and with four octal numbers, <span class=3D"ntxt">777=
7<sub>8</sub></span> up to 4095 in decimal and so on.</p><h2>Octal Number S=
ystem Example No1</h2><p>Using our previous binary number of <span class=3D=
"mtxt">1101010111001111<sub>2</sub></span> convert this binary number to it=
s octal equivalent, (base-2 to base-8).</p><table class=3D"table2"><tbody><=
tr><td style=3D"width:300px; text-align:left; line-height:1.6em; border:1px=
 solid #414143; color:#414143;">Binary Digit Value</td><td>&nbsp;<span clas=
s=3D"mtxt">001101010111001111</span>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td style=3D"width:=
300px; text-align:left; line-height:1.6em;">Group the bits into three=C2=B4=
s starting<br>from the right hand side</td><td>&nbsp;<span class=3D"mtxt">0=
01 101 010 111 001 111</span>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td style=3D"width:300px; =
text-align:left; line-height:1.6em; color:#414143;">Octal Number form</td><=
td><span class=3D"ntxt">1 5 2 7 1 7<sub>8</sub></span></td></tr></tbody></t=
able><div class=3D"bottomspace">&nbsp;</div><p>Thus, <span class=3D"mtxt">0=
01101010111001111<sub>2</sub></span> in its Binary form is equivalent to <s=
pan class=3D"ntxt">152717<sub>8</sub></span> in Octal form or 54,735 in den=
ary.</p><h2>Octal Numbers Example No2</h2><p>Convert the octal number <span=
 class=3D"ntxt">2322<sub>8</sub></span> to its decimal number equivalent, (=
base-8 to base-10).</p><table class=3D"table2"><tbody><tr><td style=3D"widt=
h:150px; text-align:left; line-height:1.6em; border:1px solid #414143; colo=
r:#414143;">Octal Digit Value</td><td style=3D"width:250px; text-align:left=
;"><span class=3D"ntxt">2322<sub>8</sub></span></td></tr><tr><td style=3D"w=
idth:150px; text-align:left; line-height:1.6em;">In polynomial form</td><td=
 style=3D"text-align:left;">=3D&nbsp;(&nbsp;<span class=3D"ntxt">2=C3=978<s=
up>3</sup></span>&nbsp;)&nbsp;+&nbsp;(&nbsp;<span class=3D"ntxt">3=C3=978<s=
up>2</sup></span>&nbsp;)&nbsp;+&nbsp;(&nbsp;<span class=3D"ntxt">2=C3=978<s=
up>1</sup></span>&nbsp;)&nbsp;+&nbsp;(&nbsp;<span class=3D"ntxt">2=C3=978<s=
up>0</sup></span>&nbsp;)</td></tr><tr><td style=3D"width:150px; text-align:=
left; line-height:1.6em;">Add the results</td><td style=3D"text-align:left;=
">=3D&nbsp;(&nbsp;<span class=3D"ntxt">1024</span>&nbsp;)&nbsp;+&nbsp;(&nbs=
p;<span class=3D"ntxt">192</span>&nbsp;)&nbsp;+&nbsp;(&nbsp;<span class=3D"=
ntxt">16</span>&nbsp;)&nbsp;+&nbsp;(&nbsp;<span class=3D"ntxt">2</span>&nbs=
p;)</td></tr><tr><td style=3D"text-align:left; line-height:1.6em;" colspan=
=3D"2">Decimal number form equals:&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<span class=3D"ntxt">12=
34<sub>10</sub></span></td></tr></tbody></table><div class=3D"bottomspace">=
&nbsp;</div><p>Then, converting octal to decimal shows that&nbsp;&nbsp;<spa=
n class=3D"ntxt">2322<sub>8</sub></span> in its Octal form is equivalent to=
 <span class=3D"ntxt">1234<sub>10</sub></span> in its Decimal form.</p><p>W=
hile <strong>Octal</strong> is another type of digital numbering system, it=
 is little used these days instead the more commonly used Hexadecimal Numbe=
ring System is used as it is more flexible.</p><div class=3D"code-block cod=
